<h5>Border and Gradient Shades</h5>

<p>The <code>$color-grade-dk</code> value is a percentage used to darken the base color for the border color. The following would use a border <code>10%</code> darker than the base color as the border color:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-grade-dk: 10%;</pre>

<p>Similarly, the <code>$color-grade-lt</code> value is a percentage used to lighten the base color for the gradient. The gradient goes from the base color to this lightened variety. The following sets a gradient that is <code>10%</code> lighter than the base on its unshadowed side:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-grade-lt: 10%;</pre>

<p>One might increase these values to add greater contrast between the border and background or between the light and dark shades of the background gradient. Use caution when increasing <code>$color-grade-lt</code> too much, as large variations may lead to a bad selection of foreground text colors over the gradient background.</p>

<h5>Light Shade</h5>

<p>The <code>.light</code> variation of any color is defined by the base color with absolute brightnesses set on three variables:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-background-light-brightness: 92%;
$color-background-shadow-light-brightness: 83%;
$color-light-border-brightness: 60%;</pre>

<h5>Dark Shade</h5>

<p>The <code>.dark</code> variation of any color is defined by the base color with absolute brightnesses set on three variables:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-background-dark-brightness: 14%;
$color-background-shadow-dark-brightness: 818%;
$color-dark-border-brightness: 40%;</pre>

<h5>Text Shades on Color Background</h5>

<p>Two possibilities exist for text on a background color, either a very light variant if the background is dark or a very dark variant if the background is light. The light text is the base color lightened by <code>$color-grade-lt-text</code> and the dark text is the base color darkened by <code>$color-grade-dk-text</code>:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-grade-dk-text: 80%;
$color-grade-lt-text: 93%;</pre>

<p>The color implementation also allows one to set the brightness threshold at which point the dark text is selected rather than light text (dark and light flavors inherit from <code>$color-contrast-threshold</code> unless explicitly defined otherwise):</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-contrast-threshold: 65%;
$color-contrast-threshold-light: 65%;
$color-contrast-threshold-dark: 65%;</pre>

<h5>Foreground Text Color</h5>

<p>When a <code>.text-[color]</code> class is used to color text, the text color is determined as an absolute brightness against the base color. This brightness value is defined by <code>$color-text-brightness</code>:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-text-brightness: 40%;</pre>

<h4>Individual Color Computation Values</h4>

<p>While WebBlocks provides a generic way for a designer to specify colors, contrasts and brightnesses, it also recognizes that individual brand and mood colors may require more sophisticated customization.</p>

<p>Each color has the following individual variants based on the above variables:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-branding-primary-dk: $color-grade-dk;
$color-branding-primary-lt: $color-grade-lt;
$color-branding-primary-background-light-brightness: $color-background-light-brightness;
$color-branding-primary-background-shadow-light-brightness: $color-background-shadow-light-brightness;
$color-branding-primary-light-border-brightness: $color-light-border-brightness;
$color-branding-primary-text-dark: shade($color-branding-primary, $color-grade-dk-text);
$color-branding-primary-text-light: tint($color-branding-primary, $color-grade-lt-text);
$color-branding-primary-contrast-threshold: $color-contrast-threshold;
$color-branding-primary-contrast-threshold-light: $color-contrast-threshold;
$color-branding-primary-text-brightness: $color-text-brightness;</pre>

<p>These variants operate by the same mechanisms as their generic "Color Computation Values" equivalents. The default bindings are shown in the above example, by any of them may have an explicit percentage or hex value as aligned with the types explained in the generic "Color Computation" section. An example of explicitly setting these values:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-branding-primary-dk: 10%;
$color-branding-primary-lt: 10%;
$color-branding-primary-background-light-brightness: 92%;
$color-branding-primary-background-shadow-light-brightness: 83%;
$color-branding-primary-light-border-brightness: 60%;
$color-branding-primary-background-dark-brightness: 14%;
$color-branding-primary-background-shadow-dark-brightness: 18%;
$color-branding-primary-dark-border-brightness: 40%;
$color-branding-primary-text-dark: #111;
$color-branding-primary-text-light: #EEE;
$color-branding-primary-contrast-threshold: 65%;
$color-branding-primary-contrast-threshold-light: 65%;
$color-branding-primary-contrast-threshold-dark 65%;
$color-branding-primary-text-brightness: 40%;</pre>

<p><span class="badge warning">WARNING</span> An exception exist to the above statement. The <code>-text-dark</code> and <code>-text-light</code> individual variables are computed values, not the same as the percentages in <code>$color-grade-dk-text</code> and <code>$color-grade-lt-text</code>.</p>

<p>Any of these values may be modified to directly influence how a single color is generated. For example, one might tweak <code>$color-branding-primary-dk</code> to influence the relative contrast of the primary border color or <code>$color-branding-primary-contrast-threshold</code> to influence where the contrast switchover point is for either dark or light text on the primary background.</p>

<h4>Individual Color Values</h4>

<p>Finally, if one does not want to use computed values, WebBlocks also directly allows you to specify the color values:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-branding-primary-background:
    lighten($color-branding-primary, $color-branding-primary-lt);

$color-branding-primary-background-shadow:
    $color-branding-primary;

$color-branding-primary-border:
    darken($color-branding-primary, $color-branding-primary-dk);

$color-branding-primary-background-text:            
    -color-select-contrast-text(
        $color-branding-primary-background, 
        $color-branding-primary-text-dark, 
        $color-branding-primary-text-light, 
        $color-branding-primary-contrast-threshold
    );

$color-branding-primary-background-text-shadow:     
    0 -1px 1px $color-branding-primary-background;

$color-branding-primary-foreground-text:           
    -color-generate-with-lightness(
        $color-branding-primary, 
        $color-branding-primary-text-brightness
    );</pre>

<p>Instead of using functions as in the above example, any of these may be set to exact hex values as desired. An example of this might be:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-branding-neutral-background: #d4d4d4;
$color-branding-neutral-background-shadow: #bbb;
$color-branding-neutral-border: #acacac;
$color-branding-neutral-background-text: #010817;
$color-branding-neutral-background-text-shadow: 0 -1px 1px #d4d4d4;</pre>

<p>The same holds true for dark and light variants, respectively appending <code>-dark</code> or <code>-light</code>, such as:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">
$color-branding-primary-background-dark: #242424;
$color-branding-neutral-background-dark-shadow: #2e2e2e;
$color-branding-neutral-dark-border: #666;
$color-branding-neutral-background-dark-text: #edf0f5;
$color-branding-neutral-background-dark-text-shadow: #242424;

$color-branding-primary-background-light: #ebebeb;
$color-branding-neutral-background-light-shadow: #d4d4d4;
$color-branding-neutral-light-border: #acacac;
$color-branding-neutral-background-light-text: #010817;
$color-branding-neutral-background-light-text-shadow: #d4d4d4;
</pre>

<p>Text color may also be explicitly defined:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$color-branding-neutral-foreground-text: #666;</pre>
    
<p>In all cases, when explicitly stating a color with a hex value, the general color computation functions will not be used for that individual value; however, they will continue to be used for all other values.</p>

